    <!-- http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00000126 -->

    <owl:Class rdf:about="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00000126">
        <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00000110"/>
        <rdfs:subClassOf>
            <owl:Restriction>
                <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002202"/>
                <owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00000104"/>
            </owl:Restriction>
        </rdfs:subClassOf>
        <rdfs:subClassOf>
            <owl:Restriction>
                <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002203"/>
                <owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00025998"/>
            </owl:Restriction>
        </rdfs:subClassOf>
        <obo:IAO_0000115>Middle germ layer of the embryo (between ectoderm and endoderm) following gastrulation (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Shortly after its formation, its cells undergo mitosis and it loses its regular epithelial architecture (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). In stage 9 it reorganizes into a regular monolayer of cuboidal cells that lines the ectoderm (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). At the end of stage 10 further cell divisions disrupt this structure and its cells reform into two layers in stage 11 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). It finally splits up into separate cell masses in late stage 11 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Its derivatives include the muscles, heart and fat body (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).</obo:IAO_0000115>
        <oboInOwl:hasDbXref>UBERON:0000926</oboInOwl:hasDbXref>
        <oboInOwl:hasOBONamespace>fly_anatomy.ontology</oboInOwl:hasOBONamespace>
        <oboInOwl:id>FBbt:00000126</oboInOwl:id>
        <oboInOwl:inSubset rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/fbbt#FB_gloss"/>
        <oboInOwl:inSubset rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/fbbt#cur"/>
        <rdfs:label>mesoderm</rdfs:label>
    </owl:Class>
    <owl:Axiom>
        <owl:annotatedSource rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00000126"/>
        <owl:annotatedProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000115"/>
        <owl:annotatedTarget>Middle germ layer of the embryo (between ectoderm and endoderm) following gastrulation (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Shortly after its formation, its cells undergo mitosis and it loses its regular epithelial architecture (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). In stage 9 it reorganizes into a regular monolayer of cuboidal cells that lines the ectoderm (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). At the end of stage 10 further cell divisions disrupt this structure and its cells reform into two layers in stage 11 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). It finally splits up into separate cell masses in late stage 11 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Its derivatives include the muscles, heart and fat body (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).</owl:annotatedTarget>
        <oboInOwl:hasDbXref>FlyBase:FBrf0089570</oboInOwl:hasDbXref>
        <oboInOwl:hasDbXref>FlyBase:FBrf0155831</oboInOwl:hasDbXref>
    </owl:Axiom>
    


    <!-- http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00000127 -->

    <owl:Class rdf:about="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00000127">
        <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00004208"/>
        <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FBbt_00005495"/>
